SIMPLE: emissary
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Emissary
<hw>Em"is*sa*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Emissaries</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L.
<ets>emissarius</ets>, fr. <ets>emittere</ets>, <ets>emissum</ets>, to
send out: cf. F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧missaire</ets>. See <er>Emit</er>.]</ety>
<def>An agent employed to advance, in a covert manner, the interests of
his employers; one sent out by any power that is at war with another, to
create dissatisfaction among the people of the latter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Buzzing <qex>emissaries</qex> fill the ears⟦br⟧
Of listening crowds with jealousies and fears.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- <er>Emissary</er>, <er>Spy</er>.</syn> <usage>A
<xex>spy</xex> is one who enters an enemy's camp or territories to learn
the condition of the enemy; an <xex>emissary</xex> may be a secret agent
appointed not only to detect the schemes of an opposing party, but to
influence their councils. A <xex>spy</xex> must be concealed, or he
suffers death; an <xex>emissary</xex> may in some cases be known as the
agent of an adversary without incurring similar hazard.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Emissary</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Emissary
<hw>Em"is*sa*ry</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Exploring;
spying.</def> <rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Applied to the veins which pass
out of the cranium through apertures in its walls.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Emissaryship</ent>⟦br⟧
